[[File:Sassanian Empire 621 A.D.jpg|thumb|300px|The province of Kushanshar was located at the eastern edge of the [[Sasanian Empire]].]] [[File:KUSHANO-SASANIANS Ardashir I Kushanshah Circa AD 230-250.jpg|thumb|300px|Kushano-Sasanian ruler [[Ardashir I Kushanshah]], circa 230-250 CE. [[Merv]] mint.]] '''Kushanshahr''' was a province of the [[Sasanian Empire]] comprising the region between [[Kabul Valley]] and [[Peshawar Valley]].<ref name="Cambridge">The Cambridge History of Iran: Seleucid Parthian, E. Yarshater, [https://books.google.com/books?id=y7IHmyKcPtYC&pg=PA770 p.770 sq]</ref> The Kushanshar territory centered on [[Tukharistan]], and covered the area from [[Tirmidh]] to [[Peshawar]].<ref name="Cambridge"/> The establishment of Sasanian rule in Kushanshar permitted the control of [[Central Asia]]n trade routes.<ref name="Cambridge"/> The [[Kushano-Sasanids]] were in charge of the area. They issued coinage which was following the [[Kushan]] standard, due to the traditional importance of trade links with [[India]].<ref name="Cambridge"/>
Kushanshahr was a pendant to [[Eranshahr]] to the West, which was the craddle of the Sasanian Empire.
Sasanian rule ended in Kushanshahr when the area was overrun by the [[Kidarites]] and then the [[Hephthalites]].<ref name="Cambridge"/> . ==See also== * [[Kushan Empire]] * [[Indo-Sasanians]] * [[Hephthalite Empire]]
